Sentiment Analysis¶

Nowadays, companies want to understand what their customers think of their products/services. For this, it uses the Natural Language Processing (NLP) technique called sentiment analysis. In this approach, textual information can be qualified with reasonable precision, in which texts are generally classified as positive, neutral or negative.

In this notebook we will show that it is possible to achieve, with a few steps, a sentiment analysis of a given text. The objective is to understand the initial steps to deal with text manipulation and how to apply them in a ML algorithm. This notebook will have Twitter and Reddit comments as a database. In this project, we train our machine algorithms with twitter data and try to classify the reddit texts. These database are public and can be found in the link below.

Tweet e Reddit

def mean_size(df):
    mean = []
    category = df['category'].unique()
    for c in category:
        d = df.loc[df['category'] == c]
        m = d['len_text'].mean()
        mean.append(m)
    
    mean_df = pd.DataFrame({'category': category, 'mean_len': mean})
    sns.barplot(x='category', y='mean_len', data= mean_df)
    
df_t['len_text'] = df_t['text'].str.len()
mean_size(df_t)

Text cleaning¶

Our data cleaning process consists of 6 steps:¶

  • Remove unicode: Unicode is a globally adopted standard that makes it possible for all characters of all written languages used on the planet to be represented on computers. However, in this set of characters there are symbols, accents, among others that would make our model less efficient.

  • Only alphabets: As we are only concerned with classifying texts. Numerical characters and punctuation we consider as noise and would make our model less efficient. Therefore, we want to extract only the alphabetic characters from the texts.

  • Lower case or upper case: All text must be capitalized or all text lowercase. Because computers understand that words like Buy and buy are distinct, which would cause noise in our model.

  • Tokenization: it's the process of segmenting running text into phrases and words. In this case we will use word tokenization. This process is crucial for the next steps.

  • Stopwords: stopwords are words like he, she, one, one, among others that can be considered irrelevant in natural language processing in most cases. If we create a Bag-of-words, for example, the highest frequency of words will be stopwords. Therefore, these words should be removed would reduce the noise of the analyzed data.

  • Normalization/Lemmatization: It aims to reduce a word to its base form and group different forms of the same word by removing the suffix and prefix from each word. Lemmatization resolves words into their dictionary form (known as a lemma), for which it requires detailed dictionaries in which the algorithm can look up and link words to the corresponding lemmas. For example, the words "running" and "ran" are all forms of the same word run. However, lemmatization without considering the part of speech (POS) can lead to some errors, for example, lemmatize("running") results in running, but lemmatize("running", pos='v') result in run.

To know more about, acess POS

In [12]:
lm = WordNetLemmatizer()

def get_wordnet_pos(treebank_tag):

    if treebank_tag.startswith('J'):
        return wordnet.ADJ
    elif treebank_tag.startswith('V'):
        return wordnet.VERB
    elif treebank_tag.startswith('R'):
        return wordnet.ADV
    else:
        return wordnet.NOUN

def text_clean(text):
    
    #Remove Unicode characters
    text = re.sub(r'[^\x00-\x7F]+', '', text)
    
    #Filter to allow only alphabets
    text = re.sub(r'[^a-zA-Z\']', ' ', text)
    
    #Converting Text to Lowercase
    text = text.lower()
    
    #tokenization
    text_tokenized = word_tokenize(text)
    
    #Lemmatization
    lemm = []
    tag = pos_tag(text_tokenized)
    stop_words = stopwords.words('english')
    for word, pos in tag:
        if word not in stop_words:
            wordnet_pos = get_wordnet_pos(pos)
            lemm.append(lm.lemmatize(word, pos=wordnet_pos))
    
    new_text = ' '.join(str(word) for word in lemm)
    
    
    return new_text

def most_words(corpus):
    word_cloud = ""
    for row in corpus:
        for word in row:
            word_cloud+=" ".join(word)
            
    wordcloud = WordCloud(width = 1000, height = 1000,
                          background_color ='white',min_font_size = 10).generate(word_cloud)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
    plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation='bilinear')

Vectorization¶

We know that machine learning algorithms only understand numbers, so the following question arises: how will we use texts for this task? There are several methodologies for transforming textual data into number data, and one of the most famous is called bag-of-words. Bag-of-word is characterized as a type of vector model that assigns weights to terms, corresponding to the number of observed occurrences of the terms in the text, that is, the frequency. Then, all words become characteristics, and the value contained represents the frequency of the word in that sentence. See example below.

I like dogs cats and
I like dogs 1 1 1 0 0
I like cats 1 1 0 1 0
I like dogs and I like cats 1 2 1 1 1

An adaptation of Bag-of_word is the Term Frequency – Inverse Document Frequency (TF-IDF). This algorithm uses the same concept of frequency of terms, but it works with an adaptation to improve its performance. In this algorithm, the words that appear the most in the set of all texts (corpus) receive a lower weight in relation to the other words. This is easily explained, as the more the word is repeated in the corpus, the less important it is for the meaning of the sentence.

Another important concept to mention is N-gram. N-gram is the probability that N words are together. Example, given the sentence I like dogs, with 2-gram would result in {I like, like dogs}, this is used because often a single word doesn't have much meaning, but a conjunction of words can give more meaning to the text. The choice of N-gram is generally according to its computational capacity, as the higher the N, the more combinations it will have, which results in greater dimensionality. In this notebook, we will use TF-IDF and N-gram to generate our word dictionary. For computational reasons, we will limit our dictionary to 10000 possibilities, as can be seen below.

In [19]:
## Tf-Idf (advanced variant of BoW with 2-gram - Twitter database
corpus = df_t["text_clean"]
vectorizer = feature_extraction.text.TfidfVectorizer(max_features=10000, ngram_range=(1,2))
vectorizer.fit(corpus)
X_train = vectorizer.transform(corpus)

Features selection¶

However, 10000 words still results in a very large dimensionality, and we are not sure if all the words are meaningful for the classes. Therefore, we made a selection of features through the independence test chi². In this type of test, we initially accept the null hypothesis, where all features are class-independent, that is, meaningless for classification. The idea here is to select only the words that are dependent for your classes, as they are the ones that will make our classifier effective. In addition, we will reduce the dimensionality of our data, which results in lower computational cost. With this method we were able to reduce our dimensionality from 10000 to 6019 words.

In [20]:
y = df_t["category"]
categories = y.unique()
X_features = vectorizer.get_feature_names()
p_value_limit = 0.95
df_features = pd.DataFrame()

for cat in categories:
    chi2, p = feature_selection.chi2(X_train, y == cat)
    df_features = df_features.append(pd.DataFrame({"feature": X_features, "score": 1-p, "y": cat}))
    df_features = df_features.sort_values(["y","score"], ascending= [True,False])
    df_features = df_features[df_features["score"] > p_value_limit]
    
X_features = df_features["feature"].unique().tolist()

Model evaluate¶

In this part we will test two distinct algorithms, Naive Bayes and Random Forest. Naive Bayes is a probabilistic algorithm based on the Bayes theorem. On the other hand, radom forest is an algorithm based on decision trees, where each forest tree votes on the classification that belongs to the sentence, and the one with the highest number of votes is the final classification.

In [24]:
def get_results(y_test, predicted, predicted_prob):
    accuracy = metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, predicted)
    auc = metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test, predicted_prob, multi_class="ovr")
    print("Accuracy:",  round(accuracy,2))
    print("Auc:", round(auc,2))
    print("Detail:")
    print(metrics.classification_report(y_test, predicted))
    
def plot_confusion_m(clf, X_test, y_test):
    plot_confusion_matrix(clf, X_test, y_test)  
    plt.show()
    
def plot_roc_curv(y_test, predicted_prob):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2)
    categories = np.unique(y_test)
    y_test_array = pd.get_dummies(y_test, drop_first=False).values

    ## Plot roc
    for i in range(len(categories)):
        fpr, tpr, thresholds = metrics.roc_curve(y_test_array[:,i], predicted_prob[:,i])
        ax[0].plot(fpr, tpr, lw=3, label='{0} (area={1:0.2f})'.format(categories[i], metrics.auc(fpr, tpr)))
        
    ax[0].plot([0,1], [0,1], color='navy', lw=3, linestyle='--')
    ax[0].set(xlim=[-0.05,1.0], ylim=[0.0,1.05], 
          xlabel='False Positive Rate', 
          ylabel="Recall", 
          title="ROC curve")
    
    ax[0].legend(loc="lower right")
    ax[0].grid(True)
    
    ## Plot precision-recall curve
    for i in range(len(categories)):
        precision, recall, thresholds = metrics.precision_recall_curve(y_test_array[:,i], predicted_prob[:,i])
        ax[1].plot(recall, precision, lw=3, 
                   label='{0} (area={1:0.2f})'.format(categories[i], metrics.auc(recall, precision)))
        
    ax[1].set(xlim=[0.0,1.05], ylim=[0.0,1.05], xlabel='Recall', ylabel="Precision", title="Precision-Recall curve")
    ax[1].legend(loc="best")
    ax[1].grid(True)
    plt.show()

Conclusions¶

Although the Random Forest classifier performed better overall than the Naive Bayes, both algorithms had low results when trying to classify the sentences from the negative class. This may have occurred due to the amount of predominant characteristics of the negative class that are present in the other classes. For example, for the negative class we selected 1591 words, of which 660 are also in the positive class, ie 41%. In relation to the neutral class, we have a total of 1074 belonging to both groups, that is, 67%. The results are presented below.
